{"type":"text","timestamp":1777215633672,"sessionID":"ses_235b21c0affearpBN37CwzRPxc","part":{"id":"prt_dca4e576b001WJqBp0H2I2cwe9","messageID":"msg_dca4de607001yN8NhPfdcY3SXz","sessionID":"ses_235b21c0affearpBN37CwzRPxc","type":"text","text":"**Comparison: Event Sourcing vs Traditional CRUD for Order Management**\n\n| Dimension | CRUD | Event Sourcing |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Consistency** | Strong, ACID on current state. Invariants enforced naturally. | Strong on event store; eventual between write/read sides (CQRS). Lag can mislead users about order status. |\n| **Query Performance** | Direct SQL queries, JOINs, aggregates. Zero sync delay. | Requires materialized projections; rebuilds are slow. Optimizable per use case, but read lag is inherent. |\n| **Learning Curve** | Low. Standard ORM/DB patterns. Mature tooling. | High. DDD, aggregates, streams, projections, versioning, snapshots. Harder debugging. |\n| **Scalability** | Vertical first. Read replicas for reads. Sharding is painful. | Natural fit for event-driven architectures. Partition by aggregate ID. Projections scale independently. |\n\n**Recommendation: Traditional CRUD — confidence ~85%**\n\nOrders demand strong consistency (no \"your order might be confirmed... check back soon\") and straightforward querying. Event sourcing's audit trail benefit is achievable with a separate audit log table — you don't need to invert your entire persistence model for it. Choose event sourcing only if temporal queries or deep event-driven microservice integration are core requirements.","time":{"start":1777215633668,"end":1777215633668}}}
